<li id="lithub_daily_widget-9" class="widget widget_lithub_daily_widget"><div class="lithub-daily-header"><a href="/category/lit-hub-daily/"><b>Lithub</b> Daily</a></div><h2 class="widgettitle">September 10, 2024</h2>
<a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hub-daily-september-10-2024/"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-242698 size-thumbnail" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/09/Screenshot-2024-09-09-at-4.29.15 PM-150x150.png" alt="whale" width="150" height="150" /></a>
<ul>
 	<li><a href="https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/i-am-herman-melville/" class="external" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400">The ill-fated collaboration between John Huston and Ray Bradbury on the production of </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400">Moby-Dick</span></i></a></li>
 	<li><a href="https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2024/09/16/the-angst-and-sorrow-of-jewish-currents" class="external" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400">On the role of </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400">Jewish Currents</span></i></a></li>
 	<li><a href="https://www.texasobserver.org/palestine-israel-texas-poetry-gaza/" class="external" target="_blank"><span style="font-weight: 400">What do we owe to language in times of unimaginable violence?</span></a></li>
</ul>
